===Etymology===
From {{inh|ja|ojp|sort=しぬ|-}}.  Appears in the oldest Japanese texts, including the ''{{w|Nihon Shoki}}'' of 720 CE and the ''{{w|Man'yōshū}}''<ref>{{RQ:Manyoshu|5|889}}, text [http://jti.lib.virginia.edu/japanese/manyoshu/Man5Yos.html#889 here]</ref> of 759 CE.<ref name="KDJ">{{R:Kokugo Dai Jiten}}</ref><ref name="DJR">{{R:Daijirin}}</ref><ref name="DJS">{{R:Daijisen}}</ref>

The {{ja-r|ぬ}} ending historically had an irregular conjugation pattern, shared only by now-obsolete verb {{m|ja|往ぬ}}, {{m|ja|去ぬ||tr=inu|go away; pass; disappear}} and auxiliary verb {{m|ja|ぬ||tr=nu|pos=indicating completion, generally reserved for non-intentional, spontaneous, or intransitive actions}}.  The {{ja-r|ぬ}} in verb {{m|ja||死ぬ}} was viewed as identical to the auxiliary,<ref name="DJS">{{R:Daijisen}}</ref> and the verb {{m|ja||死ぬ}} initially was thus never conjugated with this auxiliary as an additional suffix.<ref name="KDJ">{{R:Kokugo Dai Jiten}}</ref><ref name="DJR">{{R:Daijirin}}</ref><ref name="DJS">{{R:Daijisen}}</ref>

The auxiliary itself may have derived from the verb {{m|ja|往ぬ}}, {{m|ja|去ぬ||tr=inu|go away; pass; disappear}},<ref name="KDJ">{{R:Kokugo Dai Jiten}}</ref><ref name="DJR">{{R:Daijirin}}</ref><ref name="DJS">{{R:Daijisen}}</ref> raising the possibility that the verb {{m|ja||死ぬ}} may have derived from a fusion of {{m|ja|死||tr=shi|death}} + {{m|ja|往ぬ}}, {{m|ja|去ぬ||tr=inu|go away; pass; disappear}}.

The transition from the {{m|ja|ナ行変格活用||tr=na henkaku katsuyō|''na'' irregular conjugation}} pattern to the regular {{m|ja|四段活用||tr=yodan katsuyō|quadrigrade conjugation}} appears in texts from the {{w|Muromachi period}} (1336–1573).<ref name="KDJ">{{R:Kokugo Dai Jiten}}</ref>  The ''na'' irregular pattern persisted in increasingly limited use until the {{w|Meiji period}} (1868–1929).<ref name="DJR">{{R:Daijirin}}</ref>

